{
  "title": "[PDF] A Comparative Study of Cultural Heritage Preservation from Kyoto to ...",
  "url": "https://thesis.eur.nl/pub/75136/16830.pdf",
  "snippet": "is crucial 40 Bec et al., “Management of Immersive Heritage Tourism Experiences.” 41 Bec et al. 20 for understanding the complexities of preserving cultural heritage in modern contexts, where commercial pressures often threaten the integrity of historical sites. In Kyoto, this approach is evident in the preservation of ancient structures and practices like the Shikinen Sengu at Shimogamo Shrine. These practices ensure that heritage conservation goes beyond physical restoration to include the transmission of traditional craftsmanship, thereby maintaining cultural integrity. Tainan, though not operating under the UNESCO framework, adopts a similar approach. The city integrates local cultural practices into its preservation efforts, as seen in the restoration of Minnan architecture and [...] monuments to intangible traditions—and how it can be preserved, interpreted, and utilized. The discussion highlights heritage management approaches, particularly those adopted in Kyoto, which have aligned local conservation efforts with global recognition and increased visitor participation. “What is cultural heritage?” Cultural heritage, according to the “Recommendation concerning the Protection at National Level of the Cultural and Natural Heritage,” adopted by the General Conference of UNESCO on November 16, 1972, refers to the immeasurable heritage of mankind's shared accomplishments. 1 It includes both concrete and abstract aspects that have been transmitted through the ages. This comprehensive concept encompasses varied expressions of culture, objects of cultural significance, [...] the Tainan City Government, Kyoto Prefectural Government, and economic impact studies conducted by local universities and research institutions. This data includes visitor numbers, demographics, spending patterns, and contributions to local economies, providing a quantitative foundation for understanding the economic impacts of tourism on cultural heritage sites. Qualitative data is collected through site visits, semi-structured interviews, and document 23 analysis. Site visits to locations such as Anping Old Fort and Tainan Confucius Temple offer direct observation of interactions between tourists and heritage settings, insights into the physical condition of the sites, and the effectiveness of interpretative materials. Semi-structured interviews are conducted with a diverse range of"
}
{
  "title": "ABOUT US | Preserve Kyoto",
  "url": "https://preservekyoto.city.kyoto.lg.jp/en/about",
  "snippet": "Kyoto is a rare city in the world. It is the place of origin of Japanese　aesthetic values unique to the country and, at the same time, a still active creator of a new and unique culture, thereby serving as a source of inspiration for people around the world.  \n  \nKyoto City is currently in the midst of financial difficulties because it values the harmony between tradition, nature, and urban functions and protects its charm through strict regulations.  \n  \nIt is carrying out preservation activities to overcome such difficulties and preserve Kyoto for future generations. If people all over the world work together with us, Kyoto can survive as a beautiful city for another 100, if not, 1,000 years. [...] Kyoto is an ancient city which has preserved old cultural heritages and scenic natural beauty for over one thousand years. We cannot, however, merely take pride in past glories, nor live isolated. We must communicate widely with the world, and through international exchanges Kyoto must be always renewed culturally and continue to create her own unique culture. It is our hope, therefore, to make Kyoto a center of international cultural exchange.  \n  \n A declaration of ideals is, of course, much easier than its execution, but we, the citizens of Kyoto, would like calmly to make this resolution and pledge our efforts towards what we can do for the realization of this ideal. [...] Through this web platform, we hope to interact and work with you to pass on Kyoto for the world to the next generation."
}
{
  "title": "[PDF] Kyoto City Regional Plan for the Protection and Utilization of Cultura",
  "url": "https://www.gdrc.org/heritage/kyoto/english.pdf",
  "snippet": "Kyoto Cultural Heritage comprises lifestyle-related culture, such as local festivals, Kyoto cuisine, and kimono, and historical buildings and archaeological sites that we can easily encounter while walking. It is familiar to the citizens from children to the elderly and enriches their lives. We will understand the value of Kyoto Cultural Heritage and share it with the citizens and many other stakeholders. [...] 4 Policy on the maintenance and inheritance of Kyoto Cultural Heritage [Basic principle] Passing Kyoto Cultural Heritage onto future generations for a thousand years by offering the attraction of the city and the joy of life in Kyoto [Supporters of Kyoto Cultural Heritage] Kyoto City Museums and art museums Local residents Conservation technique holders Citizens Enterprises Universities / research institutes National government NPOs / organizations Kyoto Cultural Heritage Owners (temples, shrines, etc.) Tourists / fans Kyoto Prefecture Schools, kindergartens, etc. [...] Ninomaru-goten Palace of Nijo-jo Castle (Nakagyo Ward, National Treasure, Important Cultural Properties) Repair works on Honmaru-goten Palace of Nijo-jo Castle 7 In Kyoto, with a central focus on Kyoto Cultural Heritage, each area is working on community development by tapping into their local uniqueness. Based on this fact, we aim to enhance the value of Kyoto as a historical city to enrich the lives of citizens by utilizing Kyoto Cultural Heritage for the revitalization of communities, or incorporating it into the lives of citizens."
}
{
  "title": "Urban Heritage Strategies of Japan: Lessons for Countries in the Asia Pacific Region",
  "url": "https://www.gdrc.org/heritage/japan.html",
  "snippet": "preserve the charm of Edo-period (1603-1868) Japan. Lined with machiya (traditional wooden townhouses), stone pathways, and historic shops, these streets provide an immersive experience of Japan’s past. 5. Heritage Buildings / Houses / Features  Traditional Japanese architecture is embodied in structures such as Kyoto’s Kiyomizu-dera, Tokyo’s Meiji Shrine, and historic ryokan (traditional inns). Features like shoji (paper sliding doors), tatami flooring, and engawa (wooden verandas) reflect Japan’s architectural harmony with nature. 6. Heritage Village / Community / District / Zone  Japan’s heritage villages, such as Shirakawa-go in Gifu and Takayama’s historic district, preserve traditional thatched-roof farmhouses (gassho-zukuri) and Edo-period townscapes. These areas maintain Japan’s [...] the restoration and revitalization of traditional machiya townhouses in Kyoto by involving local residents, artisans, and businesses in the process. It aims to preserve the unique architectural character of the city while supporting local communities. | Yokai Street, Sakaiminato: The city of Sakaiminato actively involves local artists and residents in transforming the town into a lively open-air gallery showcasing sculptures of yokai (supernatural creatures from Japanese folklore). This project not only promotes local folklore but also boosts tourism and community engagement. | Tomonoura, Hiroshima: Tomonoura, a historic port town, engages local residents in heritage preservation through initiatives such as the Tomonoura Photo Library, where locals contribute their personal photographs to [...] commercial complex while preserving its iconic facade. It now houses shops, restaurants, and event spaces while retaining its architectural charm. | Kyoto International Manga Museum, Kyoto: Housed in a former elementary school building, this museum creatively repurposed the space to showcase the rich history and cultural significance of manga (Japanese comics). The adaptive reuse of the building combines heritage preservation with contemporary cultural expression. | Tennoji Park, Osaka: The revitalization of Tennoji Park involved transforming a neglected area into a vibrant urban park while preserving historic structures like the Tsutenkaku Tower. The project integrated modern recreational facilities, green spaces, and cultural elements, attracting visitors while honoring the area's"
}
{
  "title": "Historic Monuments of Ancient Kyoto (Kyoto, Uji and Otsu Cities) - UNESCO World Heritage Centre",
  "url": "https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/688",
  "snippet": "careful documentation and scientific investigation. While gardens were not well preserved in the period immediately following the Second World War, since 1965 garden conservation has been included as part of the work supported by the Agency for Cultural Affairs and is undertaken with the same attention to excavation surveys and other research. Those responsible for such work have taken great pains to ensure the use of traditional materials and techniques, to the extent of reproducing original tools. [...] In the light of the Japanese tradition of restoration and reconstruction, the buildings and gardens that compose the property retain high levels of authenticity. Although in only very rare cases have entire buildings, or even portions of them, survived intact from their construction, the rigorous respect for the original form, decoration, and materials that has prevailed in Japan for more than a millennium has ensured that what is visible today conforms in almost every detail with the original structures. This tradition has been reinforced since the end of the 19th century when the Ancient Shrines and Temples Preservation Law was enacted (1897). Only damaged portions are repaired or, if required, replaced and this work is done with careful documentation and scientific investigation. While [...] As the centre of Japanese culture for more than a thousand years, it spans the development of Japanese wooden architecture, particularly religious architecture, and the art of Japanese gardens, which has influenced landscape gardening the world over. Most of the one hundred ninety-eight buildings and twelve gardens that make up the seventeen component parts of the property were built or designed from the 10th to the 17th centuries.\n\nAll of the seventeen components of the inscribed property are religious establishments except for the castle of Nijo-jo. Together they cover a total of 1,056 hectares and are surrounded by a buffer zone of 3,579 hectares."
}